Comment in
    Semergen. 2020 Oct;46(7):439-440.

Myotonic dystrophy type 1 (DM1) or Steinert's disease (CIE-9-C: 359.21; 
CIE-10-ES: G71.11, ORPHA: 273) is a rare autosomal dominant inherited myopathy 
with almost complete penetrance and multisystemic consequences (neurological, 
cardiological, respiratory, endocrinological, and gastrointestinal). It is one 
of the clinical most variable diseases. The most bothersome symptoms for the 
patients (mobility problems, fatigue, hypersomnia, or gastrointestinal symptoms) 
and their families (apathy, lack of initiative) are not necessarily the most 
dangerous. Respiratory problems and cardiac arrhythmias shorten life expectancy. 
There is no specific treatment. The role of the Primary Care physician is 
crucial in the follow-up of DM1, either by coordinating the different 
professionals or detecting treatable complications. This work addresses the 
latter.

